Explanation of how I derived the response objects and their schemas

Step-by-step reasoning and sources inspected:
- Routes: routes/api.php shows that the API route prefix is /v1 and that posts update is exposed via Route::apiResource('posts', PostController::class)->only(['update', ...]); therefore the PATCH endpoint is /v1/posts/{post} and requires authentication (middleware auth:sanctum, verified) for the update action.
- Controller: app/Http/Controllers/Api/V1/PostController.php — update(PostsRequest $request, Post $post) authorizes 'update', updates the model with the request fields, and returns new PostResource($post). From this we infer:
  - Successful update returns a PostResource wrapped JSON response (JsonResource default wrap => top-level "data").
  - Authorization failure returns 403; missing authentication 401; route model binding not finding the Post yields 404; validation errors from PostsRequest produce 422.
- Resource: app/Http/Resources/Post.php — the PostResource toArray defines the attributes returned within the data object:
  - id (integer), title (string), slug (string), content (string), posted_at (ISO8601 string), author_id (integer), comments_count (integer), thumbnail_url (string, present only when hasThumbnail), thumb_thumbnail_url (string, present only when hasThumbnail).
  - Because JsonResource typically wraps data, the response body is { "data": { ...fields above... } }.
- Request validation: app/Http/Requests/Admin/PostsRequest.php — validated fields are title, content, posted_at (date), thumbnail_id, author_id, slug. Validation failures produce standard Laravel 422 responses with message and errors keyed by field (arrays of messages).

Based on the above, I crafted the Swagger 2.0 response objects for PATCH /v1/posts/{post} with the following status codes and schemas:
- 200: Successful update — returns the PostResource wrapped in "data", with the fields shown in PostResource.
- 401: Unauthenticated (authentication required) — simple { message } object.
- 403: Forbidden (authorization failed) — simple { message } object.
- 404: Not Found (post not found) — simple { message } object.
- 422: Validation failed — { message, errors } where errors is an object with possible keys matching validated fields (title, content, posted_at, thumbnail_id, author_id, slug), each an array of strings.

I avoided using $ref and only included fields that appear in the controller, resource, or request files mentioned.

